{{distinguish|False friend}}
'''False cognates''' are pairs of words that seem to be [[cognate]]s because of similar sounds and meaning, but have different etymologies; they can be within the same [[language]] or from different languages.{{sfnp|Moss|1992|p=?}} For example, the English word ''dog'' and the [[Mbabaram]] word ''dog'' have exactly the same meaning, [[Mbabaram language#Word for "dog"|but by complete coincidence]]. This is different from [[false friend]]s, which are similar-sounding words with different meanings, but which may in fact be etymologically related. (For example: Spanish ''dependiente'' looks like ''dependent'', but means sales assistant or clerk as well.)
Even though false cognates lack a common root, there may still be an indirect connection between them (for example by [[phono-semantic matching]] or [[folk etymology]]).
==Phenomenon== The term "false cognate" is sometimes misused to refer to [[false friend]]s, but the two phenomena are distinct.{{sfnp|Moss|1992|p=?}}{{sfnp|Chamizo-Domínguez|2008|p=166}} False friends occur when two words in different languages or dialects look similar, but have different meanings. While some false friends are also false cognates, many are genuine cognates (see [[false friend#Causes|False friends § Causes]]).{{sfnp|Chamizo-Domínguez|2008|p=166}} For example, English ''pretend'' and French ''prétendre'' are false friends, but not false cognates, as they have the same origin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=pretend |title=Pretend |work=The Online Etymological Dictionary |last=Harper |first=Douglas |authorlink=Douglas Harper |accessdate=2015-09-14}}</ref>
==Examples==
=== English ===
* English ''[[wikt:ache|ache]]'' and [[Ancient Greek language|Ancient Greek]] ἄχος ''ákhos'' (pain, distress)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Harper|first1=Douglas|title=ache|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=ache|website=Online Etymology Dictionary|publisher=Douglas Harper|accessdate=29 August 2014}}</ref> * English ''ask'' and [[Jaqaru language|Jaqaru]] ''aska''{{thin space}}<ref name="Campbell2">[[Lyle Campbell]], Historical Linguistics: An Introduction, 3rd edition, p. 350</ref> * English ''bad'' vs. [[Persian language|Persian]] {{lang|fa|بَد}} ''bad'' and [[Armenian language|Armenian]] ւադ ''vad''{{thin space}}<ref name="Campbell2"/><ref name="Glossary">{{cite book|first1=Lyle|last1=Campbell|authorlink1=Lyle Campbell|first2=Mauricio J.|last2=Mixco|title=A Glossary of Historical Linguistics|year=2007|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|ISBN=978 0 7486 2378 5|p=29}}</ref> * English ''dog'' and [[Mbabaram]] ''dog''{{thin space}}<ref name="Glossary"/> * English ''be'' and [[Gbaya language|Gbaya]] ''be''{{thin space}}<ref name="Campbell2"/> * English ''day'' and Portuguese "dia" or Spanish ''día'', or Latin ''dies'', or Italian ''dì'', or even English ''diary''{{thin space}}<ref name=oed2>[[Oxford English Dictionary]], Second edition.</ref><ref name="Glossary"/> * English ''dung'' and Korean {{lang|ko-Hang|똥}} ''ttong'' (excrement)<ref>{{cite journal|first=Samuel E.|last=Martin|year=1966|title=Lexical Evidence Relating Korean to Japanese|journal=Language|volume=42|issue=2|p=187|doi=10.2307/411687}}</ref> * English ''emoticon'' and [[Japanese language|Japanese]] {{lang|ja|絵文字}} ''[[emoji]]''{{thin space}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VPO4CgAAQBAJ|title=New Words for Old: Recycling Our Language for the Modern World|first=Caroline|last=Taggart|date=5 November 2015|publisher=Michael O'Mara Books|via=Google Books}}</ref> * English ''hollow'' and [[Lake Miwok language|Lake Miwok]] ''hóllu''{{thin space}}<ref name="Campbell2"/> * English ''much'' and Spanish ''mucho''{{thin space}}<ref name="Glossary"/> * English ''[[saint]]'' and Hindi or Sanskrit ''[[sant (religion)|sant]]''{{thin space}}<ref name="Schomer-1987">{{cite book |last1=Schomer |first1=Karine |last2=McLeod |first2=W. H. |title=The Sants: Studies in a Devotional Tradition of India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OkKhOivXrhgC |year=1987 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ. |location=Delhi |isbn=978-81-208-0277-3 |oclc=879218858 |page=3 |accessdate=7 November 2018 |quote=Thus conceptually as well as etymologically, it differs considerably from the false cognate 'saint' which is often used to translate it. Like 'saint', ''&apos;sant&apos;'' has also taken on the more general eithical meaning of the 'good person' whose life is a spiritual and moral exemplar, and is therefore attached to a wide variety of gurus, 'holy men', and other religious teachers.}}</ref> * English ''[[sheriff]]'' and Arabic ''[[sharif]]''{{thin space}}{{cn|date=November 2018}} * English ''tiny'' and [[Yana language|Yana]] ''tʼinii''{{thin space}}<ref name="Campbell2"/>
=== Others ===
* French ''feu'' (fire)<ref group="note">from Latin ''focus''</ref> and German ''Feuer'' (fire)<ref group="note">from ''*fu(w)er-'', from Proto-Germanic [[wikt:Reconstruction:Proto-Germanic/fōr|''*fōr'' ~ ''*fun-'']], see Kroonen, Guus (2013), ''Etymological Dictionary of Proto-Germanic'', Leiden: Brill</ref><ref>[[Lyle Campbell]], Historical Linguistics: An Introduction, 3rd edition, p. 355</ref><ref name="Glossary"/> * German ''haben'' and Latin ''habere'' (both "have")<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?search=have&searchmode=none Online Etymology Dictionary<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> * Greek root ''-lab-'' and [[Sanskrit]] root ''-labh-'' (take)<ref>[[Lexikon der indogermanischen Verben|LIV]] s. v. ''*sleh₂gʷ-'', ''*lembʰ-''</ref> * [[Inuktitut]] ''[[kayak]]'' and Turkish ''[[Caïque|kayık]]''<ref>{{cite journal|first=José Andrés Alonso|last=de la Fuente|title=Urban legends: Turkish kayık 'boat' and "Eskimo" Qayaq 'Kayak'|journal=Studia Linguistica Universitatis Iagellonicae Cracoviensis|year=2010|url=http://www.filg.uj.edu.pl/documents/41616/4333148/12701-Fuente.pdf|accessdate=2015-03-06}}</ref> * Malay ''mata'' and modern Greek μάτι ''máti'' (eye, from ''ommátion'')<ref name="Campbell2"/><ref name="Glossary"/> * Hungarian ''fiú'' 'son' and Romanian ''fiu'' 'son'<ref group="note">Hungarian ''fiú'' is from Proto-Uralic [[wikt:Reconstruction:Proto-Uralic/pojka|*pojka]], while Romanian ''fiu'' is from Latin ''filius''.</ref><ref name="Glossary"/> * [[Glossary of Japanese words of Portuguese origin#Arigatō|Japanese ''arigatō'' and Portuguese ''obrigado'']] (thank you) *[[Finnish language|Finnish]] ''hän'' (he/she) and [[Swedish language|Swedish]] ''han'' (he) *[[Italian language|Italian]] ''[[ciao]]'' (hello/goodbye) and [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]] ''chào'' (hello/goodbye).
